Got it—there are two separate root causes here and they’re both fixable with a tiny CSS patch.

## What’s going on (in short)
1) **Desktop top/bottom mis-alignment**  
Your media container is a `<figure>` with the browser’s default margins. That adds extra space **above/below the image column only**, so the image column’s visual top/bottom don’t line up with the text column even though the grid is stretching. Zeroing that margin fixes it. fileciteturn0file1

2) **Mobile right-edge cropping on 1st & 3rd images**  
On mobile you force the image wrapper to `aspect-ratio: 3/2`, but your actual assets are **4:3** (e.g., `width="1200" height="900"` in the HTML). A 3:2 box necessarily crops left/right on a 4:3 image—hence the missing right side you’re seeing. Switch the mobile aspect ratio to **4/3**. fileciteturn0file0 fileciteturn0file1

---

## Drop-in CSS patch (append to `assets/css/secondary-maths.css`)
```css
/* 1) Remove default <figure> margins so image/text tops & bottoms align */
.section--highlights .highlight-media { margin: 0; }

/* 2) Desktop: enforce strict 50/50 column widths for each row */
@media (min-width: 961px) {
  .section--highlights .highlight-row {
    grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; /* equal widths */
  }
}

/* 3) Mobile: match container AR to actual images (1200×900 => 4:3) to prevent side-cropping */
@media (max-width: 960px) {
  .section--highlights .highlight-media {
    aspect-ratio: 4 / 3; /* was 3 / 2 */
  }
}

/* Optional: if any subject sits toward the right edge, bias framing slightly right on mobile */
@media (max-width: 960px) {
  .section--highlights .highlight-row:nth-of-type(1) .highlight-media img,
  .section--highlights .highlight-row:nth-of-type(3) .highlight-media img {
    object-position: 60% center; /* tweak 55–70% to taste */
  }
}
```

### Why this solves both issues
- The grid already uses `align-items: stretch` and both sides set their height to `100%`, so once the `<figure>` margin is removed, the **top and bottom edges will line up perfectly** in desktop. fileciteturn0file1  
- Changing the mobile wrapper to **4:3** matches the images’ intrinsic ratio (e.g., `1200×900`), eliminating the right-edge crop you observed. fileciteturn0file0 fileciteturn0file1

If you want me to pin the 50/50 columns without touching your current `minmax(...)` setup, I can do that too—but the snippet above is the simplest, lowest-risk fix that meets your stated goals.

